The paper presents an information-theoretic cost function for co-clustering, which involves clustering two sets based on similarities between their elements. This problem is related to machine learning and data analysis, which are covered by the computer science sub-categories cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the information bottleneck formalism, which is a concept from information theory, covered by the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents experimental results on real-world datasets, which could fall under the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
